# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: tortoise-orm
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Input and output operations on a computer can be extremely slow compared to the processing of data.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] An I/O device can incorporate mechanical devices that must physically move, such as a hard drive seeking a track to read or write; this is often orders of magnitude slower than the switching of electric current.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] For example, during a disk operation that takes ten milliseconds to perform, a processor that is clocked at one gigahertz could have performed ten million instruction-processing cycles.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] A simple approach to I/O would be to start the access and then wait for it to complete.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] But such an approach, called **synchronous I/O** or **blocking I/O**, would block the progress of a program while the communication is in progress, leaving system resources idle.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] When a program makes many I/O operations (such as a program mainly or largely dependent on user input), this means that the processor can spend almost all of its time idle waiting for I/O operations to complete.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Alternatively, it is possible to start the communication and then perform processing that does not require that the I/O be completed.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] This approach is called asynchronous input/output.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Many operating system functions exist to implement asynchronous I/O at many levels.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] In fact, one of the main functions of all but the most rudimentary of operating systems is to perform at least some form of basic asynchronous I/O, though this may not be particularly apparent to the user or the programmer.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] In the simplest software solution, the hardware device status is polled at intervals to detect whether the device is ready for its next operation.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] (For example, the CP/M operating system was built this way.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Multitasking operating systems can exploit the functionality provided by hardware interrupts, whilst hiding the complexity of interrupt handling from the user.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Spooling was one of the first forms of multitasking designed to exploit asynchronous I/O.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Finally, multithreading and explicit asynchronous I/O APIs within user processes can exploit asynchronous I/O further, at the cost of extra software complexity.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Asynchronous I/O is used to improve energy efficiency, and in some cases throughput.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] However, it can have negative effects on latency and throughput in some cases.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] All forms of asynchronous I/O open applications up to potential resource conflicts and associated failure.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Careful programming (often using mutual exclusion, semaphores, etc.) is required to prevent this.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] When exposing asynchronous I/O to applications there are a few broad classes of implementation.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] The form of the API provided to the application does not necessarily correspond with the mechanism actually provided by the operating system; emulations are possible.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Furthermore, more than one method may be used by a single application, depending on its needs and the desires of its programmer(s).
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Many operating systems provide more than one of these mechanisms, it is possible that some may provide all of them.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] In a multitasking operating system, processing can be distributed across different processes, which run independently, have their own memory, and process their own I/O flows; these flows are typically connected in pipelines.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Processes are fairly expensive to create and maintain, so this solution only works well if the set of processes is small and relatively stable.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] It also assumes that the individual processes can operate independently, apart from processing each other's I/O; if they need to communicate in other ways, coordinating them can become difficult.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] An extension of this approach is dataflow programming, which allows more complicated networks than just the chains that pipes support.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Polling provides non-blocking synchronous API which may be used to implement some asynchronous API.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Available in traditional Unix and Windows.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Its major problem is that it can waste CPU time polling repeatedly when there is nothing else for the issuing process to do, reducing the time available for other processes.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Also, because a polling application is essentially single-threaded it may be unable to fully exploit I/O parallelism that the hardware is capable of.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Available in BSD Unix, and almost anything else with a TCP/IP protocol stack that either utilizes or is modeled after the BSD implementation.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] A variation on the theme of polling, a select loop uses the `select` system call to sleep until a condition occurs on a file descriptor (e.g., when data is available for reading), a timeout occurs, or a signal is received (e.g., when a child process dies).
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] By examining the return parameters of the `select` call, the loop finds out which file descriptor has changed and executes the appropriate code.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Often, for ease of use, the select loop is implemented as an event loop, perhaps using callback functions; the situation lends itself particularly well to event-driven programming.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] While this method is reliable and relatively efficient, it depends heavily on the Unix paradigm that "everything is a file"; any blocking I/O that does not involve a file descriptor will block the process.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] The select loop also relies on being able to involve all I/O in the central `select` call; libraries that conduct their own I/O are particularly problematic in this respect.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Some Unixes provide system-specific calls with better scaling; for example, `epoll` in Linux (that fills the return selection array with only those event sources on which an event has occurred), `kqueue` in FreeBSD, and event ports (and `/dev/poll`) in Solaris.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] SVR3 Unix provided the `poll` system call.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Arguably better-named than `select`, for the purposes of this discussion it is essentially the same thing.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] SVR4 Unixes (and thus POSIX) offer both calls.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] I/O is issued asynchronously, and when it is completed a signal (interrupt) is generated.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] As in low-level kernel programming, the facilities available for safe use within the signal handler are limited, and the main flow of the process could have been interrupted at nearly any point, resulting in inconsistent data structures as seen by the signal handler.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] The signal handler is usually not able to issue further asynchronous I/O by itself.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] The *signal* approach, though relatively simple to implement within the OS, brings to the application program the unwelcome baggage associated with writing an operating system's kernel interrupt system.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Its worst characteristic is that *every* blocking (synchronous) system call is potentially interruptible; the programmer must usually incorporate retry code at each call.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Available in the classic Mac OS, VMS and Windows.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Bears many of the characteristics of the *signal* method as it is fundamentally the same thing, though rarely recognized as such.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] The difference is that each I/O request usually can have its own completion function, whereas the *signal* system has a single callback.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] On the other hand, a potential problem of using callbacks is that stack depth can grow unmanageably, as an extremely common thing to do when one I/O is finished is to schedule another.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] If this should be satisfied immediately, the first callback is not 'unwound' off the stack before the next one is invoked.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Systems to prevent this (like 'mid-ground' scheduling of new work) add complexity and reduce performance.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] In practice, however, this is generally not a problem because the new I/O will itself usually return as soon as the new I/O is started allowing the stack to be 'unwound'.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] The problem can also be prevented by avoiding any further callbacks, by means of a queue, until the first callback returns.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Light-weight processes (LWPs) or threads are available in most modern operating systems.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Like the *process* method, but with lower overhead and without the data isolation that hampers coordination of the flows.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Each LWP or thread itself uses traditional blocking synchronous I/O, which simplifies programming logic; this is a common paradigm used in many programming languages including Java and Rust.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Multithreading needs to use kernel-provided synchronization mechanisms and thread-safe libraries.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] This method is most suitable for extremely large-scale applications like web servers due to the large numbers of threads needed.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] This approach is also used in the Erlang programming language runtime system.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] The Erlang virtual machine uses asynchronous I/O using a small pool of only a few threads or sometimes just one process, to handle I/O from up to millions of Erlang processes.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] I/O handling in each process is written mostly using blocking synchronous I/O.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] This way high performance of asynchronous I/O is merged with simplicity of normal I/O (cf. the Actor model).
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Many I/O problems in Erlang are mapped to message passing, which can be easily processed using built-in selective receive.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Fibers / Coroutines can be viewed as a similarly lightweight approach to do asynchronous I/O outside of the Erlang runtime system, although they do not provide exactly the same guarantees as Erlang processes.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Available in Microsoft Windows, Solaris, AmigaOS, DNIX and Linux (using io_uring, available on 5.1 and above).
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] I/O requests are issued asynchronously, but notifications of completion are provided via a synchronizing queue mechanism in the order they are completed.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Usually associated with a state-machine structuring of the main process (event-driven programming), which can bear little resemblance to a process that does not use asynchronous I/O or that uses one of the other forms, hampering code reuse.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Does not require additional special synchronization mechanisms or thread-safe libraries, nor are the textual (code) and time (event) flows separated.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Available in VMS and AmigaOS (often used in conjunction with a completion port).
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Bears many of the characteristics of the *completion queue* method, as it is essentially a completion queue of depth one.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] To simulate the effect of queue 'depth', an additional event flag is required for each potential unprocessed (but completed) event, or event information can be lost.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Waiting for the next available event in such a clump requires synchronizing mechanisms that may not scale well to larger numbers of potentially parallel events.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Available in mainframes by IBM, Groupe Bull, and Unisys.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Channel I/O is designed to maximize CPU utilization and throughput by offloading most I/O onto a coprocessor.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] The coprocessor has onboard DMA, handles device interrupts, is controlled by the main CPU, and only interrupts the main CPU when it's truly necessary.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] This architecture also supports so-called channel programs that run on the channel processor to do heavy lifting for I/O activities and protocols.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Available in Windows Server 2012 and Windows 8.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Optimized for applications that process large numbers of small messages to achieve higher I/O operations per second with reduced jitter and latency.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] The vast majority of general-purpose computing hardware relies entirely upon two methods of implementing asynchronous I/O: polling and interrupts.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Usually both methods are used together, the balance depends heavily upon the design of the hardware and its required performance characteristics.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Pure polling systems are entirely possible, small microcontrollers (such as systems using the PIC microcontroller) are often built this way.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] CP/M systems could also be built this way (though rarely were), with or without DMA.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Also, when the utmost performance is necessary for only a *few* tasks, at the expense of any other potential tasks, polling may also be appropriate as the overhead of taking interrupts may be unwelcome.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Most general-purpose computing systems rely heavily upon interrupts.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] A pure interrupt system may be possible, though usually some component of polling is also required, as it is very common for multiple potential sources of interrupts to share a common interrupt signal line, in which case polling is used within the device driver to resolve the actual source.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] (This resolution time also contributes to an interrupt system's performance penalty.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Over the years a great deal of work has been done to try to minimize the overhead associated with servicing an interrupt.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Hybrid approaches are also possible, wherein an interrupt can trigger the beginning of some burst of asynchronous I/O, and polling is used within the burst itself.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] This technique is common in high-speed device drivers, such as network or disk, where the time lost in returning to the pre-interrupt task is greater than the time until the next required servicing.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] (Common I/O hardware in use these days relies heavily upon DMA and large data buffers to make up for a relatively poorly-performing interrupt system.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] These characteristically use polling inside the driver loops, and can exhibit tremendous throughput.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] At one time this sort of hybrid approach was common in disk and network drivers where there was not DMA or significant buffering available.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] (In effect using the processor itself as a DMA engine.) The 6502 processor offered an unusual means to provide a three-element per-datum loop, as it had a hardware pin that, when asserted, would cause the processor's Overflow bit to be set directly.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Using only these two tools (polling, and interrupts), all the other forms of asynchronous I/O discussed above may be (and in fact, are) synthesized.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] In an environment such as a Java virtual machine (JVM), asynchronous I/O can be synthesized *even though* the environment the JVM is running in may not offer it at all.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] This is due to the interpreted nature of the JVM.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] The JVM may poll (or take an interrupt) periodically to institute an internal flow of control change, effecting the appearance of multiple simultaneous processes, at least some of which presumably exist in order to perform asynchronous I/O.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] That, in fact, is the problem with using polling in any form to synthesize a different form of asynchronous I/O.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Every CPU cycle that is a poll is wasted, and lost to overhead rather than accomplishing a desired task.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Every CPU cycle that is *not* a poll represents an increase in latency of reaction to pending I/O.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Striking an acceptable balance between these two opposing forces is difficult.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] The trick to maximize efficiency is to minimize the amount of work that has to be done upon reception of an interrupt in order to awaken the appropriate application.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Secondarily (but perhaps no less important) is the method the application itself uses to determine what it needs to do.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Particularly problematic (for application efficiency) are the exposed polling methods, including the select/poll mechanisms.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Though the underlying I/O events they are interested in are in all likelihood interrupt-driven, the interaction *to* this mechanism is polled and can consume a large amount of time in the poll.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] This is particularly true of the potentially large-scale polling possible through select (and poll).
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] Interrupts map very well to Signals, Callback functions, Completion Queues, and Event flags, such systems can be very efficient.
[src:tortoise-orm/asynchronous-i-o] The following examples show three approaches to reading I/O.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-mapper-pattern] In software engineering, the **data mapper pattern** is an architectural pattern.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-mapper-pattern] It was named by Martin Fowler in his 2003 book *Patterns of Enterprise Application Architecture*.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-mapper-pattern] The interface of an object conforming to this pattern would include functions such as Create, Read, Update, and Delete, that operate on objects that represent domain entity types in a data store.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-mapper-pattern] A Data Mapper is a Data Access Layer that performs bidirectional transfer of data between a persistent data store (often a relational database) and an in-memory data representation (the domain layer).
[src:tortoise-orm/data-mapper-pattern] The goal of the pattern is to keep the in-memory representation and the persistent data store independent of each other and the data mapper itself.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-mapper-pattern] This is useful when one needs to model and enforce strict business processes on the data in the domain layer that do not map neatly to the persistent data store.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-mapper-pattern] The layer is composed of one or more mappers (or Data Access Objects), performing the data transfer.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-mapper-pattern] Generic mappers will handle many different domain entity types; dedicated mappers will handle one or a few.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-mapper-pattern] Implementations of the concept can be found in various frameworks for many programming environments.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] A **data model** is an abstract model that organizes elements of data and standardizes how they relate to one another and to the properties of real-world entities.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] For instance, a data model may specify that the data element representing a car be composed of a number of other elements which, in turn, represent the color and size of the car and define its owner.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] The corresponding professional activity is called generally *data modeling* or, more specifically, *database design*.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Data models are typically specified by a data expert, data specialist, data scientist, data librarian, or a data scholar.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] A data modeling language and notation are often represented in graphical form as diagrams.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] A data model can sometimes be referred to as a data structure, especially in the context of programming languages.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Data models are often complemented by function models, especially in the context of enterprise models.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] A data model explicitly determines the *structure of data*; conversely, **structured data** is data organized according to an explicit data model or data structure.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Structured data is in contrast to *unstructured data* and *semi-structured data*.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] The term ***data model*** can refer to two distinct but closely related concepts.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Sometimes it refers to an abstract formalization of the objects and relationships found in a particular application domain: for example the customers, products, and orders found in a manufacturing organization.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] At other times it refers to the set of concepts used in defining such formalizations: for example concepts such as entities, attributes, relations, or tables.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] So the "data model" of a banking application may be defined using the entity–relationship "data model".
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] This article uses the term in both senses.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Managing large quantities of structured and unstructured data is a primary function of information systems.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Data models describe the structure, manipulation, and integrity aspects of the data stored in data management systems such as relational databases.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] They may also describe data with a looser structure, such as word processing documents, email messages, pictures, digital audio, and video: XDM, for example, provides a data model for XML documents.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] The main aim of data models is to support the development of information systems by providing the definition and format of data.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] According to West and Fowler (1999) "if this is done consistently across systems then compatibility of data can be achieved.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] If the same data structures are used to store and access data then different applications can share data.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] The results of this are indicated above.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] However, systems and interfaces often cost more than they should, to build, operate, and maintain.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] They may also constrain the business rather than support it.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] A major cause is that the quality of the data models implemented in systems and interfaces is poor".
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] The reason for these problems is a lack of standards that will ensure that data models will both meet business needs and be consistent.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] A data model explicitly determines the structure of data.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Typical applications of data models include database models, design of information systems, and enabling exchange of data.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Logical data model: describes the semantics, as represented by a particular data manipulation technology.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] This consists of descriptions of tables and columns, object oriented classes, and XML tags, among other things.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Physical data model: describes the physical means by which data are stored.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] This is concerned with partitions, CPUs, tablespaces, and the like.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] The significance of this approach, according to ANSI, is that it allows the three perspectives to be relatively independent of each other.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Storage technology can change without affecting either the logical or the conceptual model.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] The table/column structure can change without (necessarily) affecting the conceptual model.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] In each case, of course, the structures must remain consistent with the other model.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] The table/column structure may be different from a direct translation of the entity classes and attributes, but it must ultimately carry out the objectives of the conceptual entity class structure.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Early phases of many software development projects emphasize the design of a conceptual data model.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Such a design can be detailed into a logical data model.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] In later stages, this model may be translated into physical data model.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] However, it is also possible to implement a conceptual model directly.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] One of the earliest pioneering works in modeling information systems was done by Young and Kent (1958), who argued for "a precise and abstract way of specifying the informational and time characteristics of a data processing problem".
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] They wanted to create "a notation that should enable the analyst to organize the problem around any piece of hardware".
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Their work was the first effort to create an abstract specification and invariant basis for designing different alternative implementations using different hardware components.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] The next step in IS modeling was taken by CODASYL, an IT industry consortium formed in 1959, who essentially aimed at the same thing as Young and Kent: the development of "a proper structure for machine-independent problem definition language, at the system level of data processing".
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] This led to the development of a specific IS information algebra.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] In the 1960s data modeling gained more significance with the initiation of the management information system (MIS) concept.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] According to Leondes (2002), "during that time, the information system provided the data and information for management purposes.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] The first generation database system, called Integrated Data Store (IDS), was designed by Charles Bachman at General Electric.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Two famous database models, the network data model and the hierarchical data model, were proposed during this period of time".
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Codd worked out his theories of data arrangement, and proposed the relational model for database management based on first-order predicate logic.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] In the 1970s entity–relationship modeling emerged as a new type of conceptual data modeling, originally formalized in 1976 by Peter Chen.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Entity–relationship models were being used in the first stage of information system design during the requirements analysis to describe information needs or the type of information that is to be stored in a database.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] This technique can describe any ontology, i.e., an overview and classification of concepts and their relationships, for a certain area of interest.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Nijssen developed "Natural Language Information Analysis Method" (NIAM) method, and developed this in the 1980s in cooperation with Terry Halpin into Object–Role Modeling (ORM).
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] However, it was Terry Halpin's 1989 PhD thesis that created the formal foundation on which Object–Role Modeling is based.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Bill Kent, in his 1978 book *Data and Reality,* compared a data model to a map of a territory, emphasizing that in the real world, "highways are not painted red, rivers don't have county lines running down the middle, and you can't see contour lines on a mountain".
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] In contrast to other researchers who tried to create models that were mathematically clean and elegant, Kent emphasized the essential messiness of the real world, and the task of the data modeler to create order out of chaos without excessively distorting the truth.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Harrington (2000), "the development of the object-oriented paradigm brought about a fundamental change in the way we look at data and the procedures that operate on data.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Traditionally, data and procedures have been stored separately: the data and their relationship in a database, the procedures in an application program.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] During the early 1990s, three Dutch mathematicians Guido Bakema, Harm van der Lek, and JanPieter Zwart, continued the development on the work of G.M.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] They focused more on the communication part of the semantics.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] In 1997 they formalized the method Fully Communication Oriented Information Modeling FCO-IM.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] A database model is a specification describing how a database is structured and used.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Several such models have been suggested.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] This may not strictly qualify as a data model.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] The flat (or table) model consists of a single, two-dimensional array of data elements, where all members of a given column are assumed to be similar values, and all members of a row are assumed to be related to one another.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] The hierarchical model is similar to the network model except that links in the hierarchical model form a tree structure, while the network model allows arbitrary graph.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] , organizes data using two fundamental constructs, called records and sets.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Records (or nodes) contain fields (i.e. attributes), and sets (or edges) define one-to-many, many-to-many and many-to-one relationships between records: one owner, many members.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] The network data model is an abstraction of the design concept used in the implementation of databases.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Network models emphasise interconnectedness, making them ideal for applications where relationships are crucial, like social networks or recommendation systems.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] This structure allows for efficient querying of relationships without expensive joins.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] is a database model based on first-order predicate logic.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Its core idea is to describe a database as a collection of predicates over a finite set of predicate variables, describing constraints on the possible values and combinations of values.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] The power of the relational data model lies in its mathematical foundations and a simple user-level paradigm.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] A method of data modeling that has been defined as "attribute free", and "fact-based".
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] The result is a verifiably correct system, from which other common artifacts, such as ERD, UML, and semantic models may be derived.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Associations between data objects are described during the database design procedure, such that normalization is an inevitable result of the process.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] The simplest style of data warehouse schema.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] The star schema consists of a few "fact tables" (possibly only one, justifying the name) referencing any number of "dimension tables".
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] A data structure diagram (DSD) is a diagram and data model used to describe conceptual data models by providing graphical notations which document entities and their relationships, and the constraints that bind them.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] The basic graphic elements of DSDs are boxes, representing entities, and arrows, representing relationships.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Data structure diagrams are most useful for documenting complex data entities.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Data structure diagrams are an extension of the entity–relationship model (ER model).
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] In DSDs, attributes are specified inside the entity boxes rather than outside of them, while relationships are drawn as boxes composed of attributes which specify the constraints that bind entities together.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] DSDs differ from the ER model in that the ER model focuses on the relationships between different entities, whereas DSDs focus on the relationships of the elements within an entity and enable users to fully see the links and relationships between each entity.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] There are several styles for representing data structure diagrams, with the notable difference in the manner of defining cardinality.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] The choices are between arrow heads, inverted arrow heads (crow's feet), or numerical representation of the cardinality.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] An entity–relationship model (ERM), sometimes referred to as an entity–relationship diagram (ERD), could be used to represent an abstract conceptual data model (or semantic data model or physical data model) used in software engineering to represent structured data.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] There are several notations used for ERMs.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Like DSD's, attributes are specified inside the entity boxes rather than outside of them, while relationships are drawn as lines, with the relationship constraints as descriptions on the line.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] The E-R model, while robust, can become visually cumbersome when representing entities with several attributes.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] There are several styles for representing data structure diagrams, with a notable difference in the manner of defining cardinality.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] A data model in Geographic information systems is a mathematical construct for representing geographic objects or surfaces as data.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Generic data models are generalizations of conventional data models.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] They define standardized general relation types, together with the kinds of things that may be related by such a relation type.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Generic data models are developed as an approach to solving some shortcomings of conventional data models.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] For example, different modelers usually produce different conventional data models of the same domain.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] This can lead to difficulty in bringing the models of different people together and is an obstacle for data exchange and data integration.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Invariably, however, this difference is attributable to different levels of abstraction in the models and differences in the kinds of facts that can be instantiated (the semantic expression capabilities of the models).
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] The modelers need to communicate and agree on certain elements that are to be rendered more concretely, in order to make the differences less significant.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] A semantic data model in software engineering is a technique to define the meaning of data within the context of its interrelationships with other data.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] A semantic data model is an abstraction that defines how the stored symbols relate to the real world.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] A semantic data model is sometimes called a conceptual data model.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] The logical data structure of a database management system (DBMS), whether hierarchical, network, or relational, cannot totally satisfy the requirements for a conceptual definition of data because it is limited in scope and biased toward the implementation strategy employed by the DBMS.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Therefore, the need to define data from a conceptual view has led to the development of semantic data modeling techniques.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] That is, techniques to define the meaning of data within the context of its interrelationships with other data.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] The real world, in terms of resources, ideas, events, etc., are symbolically defined within physical data stores.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Thus, the model must be a true representation of the real world.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Data architecture is the design of data for use in defining the target state and the subsequent planning needed to hit the target state.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] It is usually one of several architecture domains that form the pillars of an enterprise architecture or solution architecture.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] A data architecture describes the data structures used by a business and/or its applications.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] There are descriptions of data in storage and data in motion; descriptions of data stores, data groups, and data items; and mappings of those data artifacts to data qualities, applications, locations, etc.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Essential to realizing the target state, Data architecture describes how data is processed, stored, and utilized in a given system.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] It provides criteria for data processing operations that make it possible to design data flows and also control the flow of data in the system.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Data modeling in software engineering is the process of creating a data model by applying formal data model descriptions using data modeling techniques.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Data modeling is a technique for defining business requirements for a database.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] It is sometimes called *database modeling* because a data model is eventually implemented in a database.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] The figure illustrates the way data models are developed and used today.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] A conceptual data model is developed based on the data requirements for the application that is being developed, perhaps in the context of an activity model.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] The data model will normally consist of entity types, attributes, relationships, integrity rules, and the definitions of those objects.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] This is then used as the start point for interface or database design.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Another kind of data model describes how to organize data using a database management system or other data management technology.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] It describes, for example, relational tables and columns or object-oriented classes and attributes.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Such a data model is sometimes referred to as the *physical data model*, but in the original ANSI three schema architecture, it is called "logical".
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] In that architecture, the physical model describes the storage media (cylinders, tracks, and tablespaces).
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Ideally, this model is derived from the more conceptual data model described above.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] It may differ, however, to account for constraints like processing capacity and usage patterns.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] A different approach is to use adaptive systems such as artificial neural networks that can autonomously create implicit models of data.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] A data structure is a way of storing data in a computer so that it can be used efficiently.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] It is an organization of mathematical and logical concepts of data.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Often a carefully chosen data structure will allow the most efficient algorithm to be used.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] The choice of the data structure often begins from the choice of an abstract data type.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] A data model describes the structure of the data within a given domain and, by implication, the underlying structure of that domain itself.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] This means that a data model in fact specifies a dedicated *grammar* for a dedicated artificial language for that domain.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] A data model represents classes of entities (kinds of things) about which a company wishes to hold information, the attributes of that information, and relationships among those entities and (often implicit) relationships among those attributes.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] The model describes the organization of the data to some extent irrespective of how data might be represented in a computer system.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] The entities represented by a data model can be the tangible entities, but models that include such concrete entity classes tend to change over time.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Robust data models often identify abstractions of such entities.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] For example, a data model might include an entity class called "Person", representing all the people who interact with an organization.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Such an abstract entity class is typically more appropriate than ones called "Vendor" or "Employee", which identify specific roles played by those people.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] A data model *instance*, i.e. applying a data model *theory* to create a practical data model *instance* for some particular application.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] For example, in the relational model, the structural part is based on a modified concept of the mathematical relation; the integrity part is expressed in first-order logic and the manipulation part is expressed using the relational algebra, tuple calculus and domain calculus.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] A data model instance is created by applying a data model theory.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] This is typically done to solve some business enterprise requirement.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Business requirements are normally captured by a semantic logical data model.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] This is transformed into a physical data model instance from which is generated a physical database.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] For example, a data modeler may use a data modeling tool to create an entity–relationship model of the corporate data repository of some business enterprise.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] This model is transformed into a relational model, which in turn generates a relational database.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Patterns are common data modeling structures that occur in many data models.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] A data-flow diagram (DFD) is a graphical representation of the "flow" of data through an information system.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] It differs from the flowchart as it shows the *data* flow instead of the *control* flow of the program.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] A data-flow diagram can also be used for the visualization of data processing (structured design).
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Data-flow diagrams were invented by Larry Constantine, the original developer of structured design, based on Martin and Estrin's "data-flow graph" model of computation.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] It is common practice to draw a context-level data-flow diagram first which shows the interaction between the system and outside entities.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] The **DFD** is designed to show how a system is divided into smaller portions and to highlight the flow of data between those parts.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] An Information model is not a type of data model, but more or less an alternative model.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Within the field of software engineering, both a data model and an information model can be abstract, formal representations of entity types that include their properties, relationships and the operations that can be performed on them.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] The entity types in the model may be kinds of real-world objects, such as devices in a network, or they may themselves be abstract, such as for the entities used in a billing system.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Typically, they are used to model a constrained domain that can be described by a closed set of entity types, properties, relationships and operations.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] According to Lee (1999) an information model is a representation of concepts, relationships, constraints, rules, and operations to specify data semantics for a chosen domain of discourse.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] It can provide sharable, stable, and organized structure of information requirements for the domain context.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] More in general the term *information model* is used for models of individual things, such as facilities, buildings, process plants, etc.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] In those cases the concept is specialised to Facility Information Model, Building Information Model, Plant Information Model, etc.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Such an information model is an integration of a model of the facility with the data and documents about the facility.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] An information model provides formalism to the description of a problem domain without constraining how that description is mapped to an actual implementation in software.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] There may be many mappings of the information model.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Such mappings are called data models, irrespective of whether they are object models (e.g. using UML), entity–relationship models or XML schemas.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] An object model in computer science is a collection of objects or classes through which a program can examine and manipulate some specific parts of its world.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] In other words, the object-oriented interface to some service or system.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Such an interface is said to be the *object model of* the represented service or system.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] For example, the Document Object Model (DOM) is a collection of objects that represent a page in a web browser, used by script programs to examine and dynamically change the page.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] There is a Microsoft Excel object model for controlling Microsoft Excel from another program, and the ASCOM Telescope Driver is an object model for controlling an astronomical telescope.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] In computing the term *object model* has a distinct second meaning of the general properties of objects in a specific computer programming language, technology, notation or methodology that uses them.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] For example, the *Java object model*, the *COM object model*, or *the object model of OMT*.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Such object models are usually defined using concepts such as class, message, inheritance, polymorphism, and encapsulation.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] There is an extensive literature on formalized object models as a subset of the formal semantics of programming languages.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Object–Role Modeling (ORM) is a method for conceptual modeling, and can be used as a tool for information and rules analysis.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] Object–Role Modeling is a fact-oriented method for performing systems analysis at the conceptual level.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] The quality of a database application depends critically on its design.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] To help ensure correctness, clarity, adaptability and productivity, information systems are best specified first at the conceptual level, using concepts and language that people can readily understand.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] The conceptual design may include data, process and behavioral perspectives, and the actual DBMS used to implement the design might be based on one of many logical data models (relational, hierarchic, network, object-oriented, etc.).
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] The Unified Modeling Language (UML) is a standardized general-purpose modeling language in the field of software engineering.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] It is a graphical language for visualizing, specifying, constructing, and documenting the artifacts of a software-intensive system.
[src:tortoise-orm/data-model] UML offers a mix of functional models, data models, and database models.
[src:tortoise-orm/getting-started] Tortoise ORM requires **Python 3.10** or later.
[src:tortoise-orm/getting-started] Define the models by inheriting from `tortoise.models.Model`.
[src:tortoise-orm/getting-started] After defining the models, Tortoise ORM needs to be initialized to establish the relationships between models and connect to the database.
[src:tortoise-orm/getting-started] The code below creates a connection to a SQLite DB database with the `aiosqlite` client.
[src:tortoise-orm/getting-started] `generate_schema` sets up schema on an empty database.
[src:tortoise-orm/getting-started] `generate_schema` is for development purposes only, see Migrations for schema migration tools.
[src:tortoise-orm/getting-started] `run_async` is a helper function to run simple Tortoise scripts.
[src:tortoise-orm/getting-started] For production use, see Tortoise-ORM FastAPI integration, Tortoise-ORM Sanic integration and other integrations, as welll as check out The Importance of Cleaning Up.
[src:tortoise-orm/getting-started] Find more examples (including transactions, using multiple databases and more complex querying) in Examples and Query API.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] All models should be derived from `Model`.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] To start describing the models, import `Model` from `tortoise.models`.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] Every model should be derived from `Model` or its subclasses.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] This model will not affect the schema, but it will be available for inheritance.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] Further we have field `fields.DatetimeField(auto_now=True)`.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] Options `auto_now` and `auto_now_add` work like Django’s options — they are handled purely in Python and do **not** add a `DEFAULT` clause to the database schema.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] If you define the variable `__models__` in the module which you load your models from, `generate_schema` will use that list, rather than automatically finding models for you.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] In Tortoise ORM, every model must have a primary key.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] That primary key will be accessible through a reserved field `pk` which will be an alias of whichever field has been nominated as a primary key.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] That alias field can be used as a field name when doing filtering e.g.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] One must define a primary key by setting the `primary_key` parameter to `True`.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] If you don’t define a primary key, the primary key will be generated as an `IntField` with name of `id`.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] If this is used on an Integer Field, `generated` will be set to `True` unless you explicitly pass `generated=False` as well.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] When defining models in Tortoise ORM, you can save a lot of repetitive work by leveraging from inheritance.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] You can define fields in more generic classes and they are automatically available in derived classes.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] Base classes are not limited to Model classes.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] This way you are able to define your models in a natural and easy to maintain way.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] Using the `Meta` class is not necessary.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] But it is a good habit, to give your table an explicit name.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] This way you can change the model name without breaking the schema.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] The `Meta` class is used to configure metadata for the Model.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] Specify `unique_together` to set up compound unique indexes for sets of columns.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] Specify `indexes` to set up compound non-unique indexes for sets of columns.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] Specify `constraints` to add named database constraints to the model.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] Supports `UniqueConstraint` and `CheckConstraint` objects, which are tracked by the migration autodetector and generate `AddConstraint`, `RemoveConstraint`, and `RenameConstraint` operations automatically.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] `unique_together` is the legacy way to define compound unique indexes.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] `constraints` with `UniqueConstraint` objects is preferred for new code, as it supports explicit naming, partial indexes (PostgreSQL), and is handled by the migration framework.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] Specify `ordering` to set up default ordering for given model.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] It should be iterable of strings formatted in same way as `.order_by(...)` receives.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] If query is built with `GROUP_BY` clause using `.annotate(...)` default ordering is not applied.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] When `True` (the default), after an INSERT on a non-RETURNING backend (e.g.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] MySQL), Tortoise will issue a follow-up `SELECT` to fetch database-applied default values for fields declared with `db_default`.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] Set to `False` to skip the extra query when you don’t need the database-generated values back on the Python instance immediately.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] On RETURNING backends (PostgreSQL, SQLite) the values are always returned in the INSERT response regardless of this setting.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] Specify `manager` to override the default manager.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] It should be instance of `tortoise.manager.Manager` or subclass.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] In event model we got some more fields, that could be interesting for us.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] Here we create foreign key reference to tournament.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] You can refer to the model either by string literal (`"app_name.ModelName"`) or by passing the model class directly (e.g.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] String references are required for forward references where the target model is not yet defined.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] `models` is default app name, but you can change it in `class Meta` with `app = 'other'`.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] A `ForeignKeyField` is a virtual field, meaning it has no direct DB backing.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] Instead it has a field (by default called `*FKNAME*_id` (that is, just an `_id` is appended) that is the actual DB-backing field.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] It will just contain the Key value of the related table.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] This is an important detail as it would allow one to assign/read the actual value directly, which could be considered an optimization if the entire foreign object isn’t needed.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] Querying a relationship is typically done by appending a double underscore, and then the foreign object’s field.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] Then a normal query attr can be appended.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] Fetching foreign keys can be done with both async and sync interfaces.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] To get the Reverse-FK, e.g. an *event.tournament* we currently only support the sync interface.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] Next field is `fields.ManyToManyField('models.Team', related_name='events')`.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] It describes many to many relation to model Team.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] To add to a `ManyToManyField` both the models need to be saved, else you will get an `OperationalError` raised.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] Resolving many to many fields can be done with both async and sync interfaces.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] The reverse lookup of `team.event_team` works exactly the same way.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] Since Tortoise ORM is still a young project, it does not have such widespread support by various editors who help you writing code using good autocomplete for models and different relations between them.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] However, you can get such autocomplete by doing a little work yourself.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] All you need to do is add a few annotations to your models for fields that are responsible for the relations.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] Here is an updated example from Getting started, that will add autocomplete for all models including fields for the relations between models.
