[src:tortoise-orm/models] Specific DB connection to use instead of default bound.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] Register listener to current model class for special Signal.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] Creates/Updates the current model object.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] If provided, it should be a tuple/list of fields by name.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] This is the subset of fields that should be updated.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] If the object needs to be created `update_fields` will be ignored.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] Returns a queryset that will lock rows until the end of the transaction, generating a SELECT … FOR UPDATE SQL statement on supported databases.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] Updates the current model with the provided dict.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] This can allow mass-updating a model from a dict, also ensuring that datatype conversions happen.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] This will ignore any extra fields, and NOT update the model with them, but will raise errors on bad types or updating Many-instance relations.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] A convenience method for updating an object with the given kwargs, creating a new one if necessary.
[src:tortoise-orm/models] Default values used to update the object.
[src:tortoise-orm/object-relational-mapping] In object-oriented programming, data-management tasks act on objects that combine scalar values into objects.
[src:tortoise-orm/object-relational-mapping] For example, consider an address book entry that represents a single person along with zero or more phone numbers and zero or more addresses.
[src:tortoise-orm/object-relational-mapping] This could be modeled in an object-oriented implementation by a "Person object" with an attribute/field to hold each data item that the entry comprises: the person's name, a list of phone numbers, and a list of addresses.
[src:tortoise-orm/object-relational-mapping] The list of phone numbers would itself contain "PhoneNumber objects" and so on.
[src:tortoise-orm/object-relational-mapping] Each such address-book entry is treated as a single object by the programming language (it can be referenced by a single variable containing a pointer to the object, for instance).
[src:tortoise-orm/object-relational-mapping] Various methods can be associated with the object, such as methods to return the preferred phone number, the home address, and so on.
[src:tortoise-orm/object-relational-mapping] By contrast, relational databases, such as SQL, group scalars into tuples, which are then enumerated in tables.
[src:tortoise-orm/object-relational-mapping] Tuples and objects have some general similarity, in that they are both ways to collect values into named fields such that the whole collection can be manipulated as a single compound entity.
[src:tortoise-orm/object-relational-mapping] They have many differences, though, in particular: lifecycle management (row insertion and deletion, versus garbage collection or reference counting), references to other entities (object references, versus foreign key references), and inheritance (non-existent in relational databases).
[src:tortoise-orm/object-relational-mapping] As well, objects are managed on-heap and are under full control of a single process, while database tuples are shared and must incorporate locking, merging, and retry.
[src:tortoise-orm/object-relational-mapping] Object–relational mapping provides automated support for mapping tuples to objects and back, while accounting for all of these differences.
[src:tortoise-orm/object-relational-mapping] The heart of the problem involves translating the logical representation of the objects into an atomized form that is capable of being stored in the database while preserving the properties of the objects and their relationships so that they can be reloaded as objects when needed.
[src:tortoise-orm/object-relational-mapping] If this storage and retrieval functionality is implemented, the objects are said to be persistent.
[src:tortoise-orm/object-relational-mapping] Implementation-specific details of storage drivers are generally wrapped in an API in the programming language in use, exposing methods to interact with the storage medium in a way which is simpler and more in line with the paradigms of surrounding code.
[src:tortoise-orm/object-relational-mapping] The following is a simple example, written in C# code, to execute a query written in SQL using a database engine.
[src:tortoise-orm/object-relational-mapping] In contrast, the following makes use of an ORM-job API which makes it possible to write code that naturally makes use of the features of the language.
[src:tortoise-orm/object-relational-mapping] The case above makes use of an object representing the storage repository and methods of that object.
[src:tortoise-orm/object-relational-mapping] Other frameworks might provide code as static methods, as in the example below, and yet other methods may not implement an object-oriented system at all.
[src:tortoise-orm/object-relational-mapping] Often the choice of paradigm is made for the best fit of the ORM into the surrounding language's design principles.
[src:tortoise-orm/object-relational-mapping] Compared to traditional techniques of exchange between an object-oriented language and a relational database, ORM often reduces the amount of code that needs to be written.
[src:tortoise-orm/object-relational-mapping] Disadvantages of ORM tools generally stem from the high level of abstraction obscuring what is actually happening in the implementation code.
[src:tortoise-orm/object-relational-mapping] Another approach is to use an object-oriented database management system (OODBMS) or document-oriented databases such as native XML databases that provide more flexibility in data modeling.
[src:tortoise-orm/object-relational-mapping] OODBMSs are databases designed specifically for working with object-oriented values.
[src:tortoise-orm/object-relational-mapping] Using an OODBMS eliminates the need for converting data to and from its SQL form, as the data is stored in its original object representation and relationships are directly represented, rather than requiring join tables/operations.
[src:tortoise-orm/object-relational-mapping] The equivalent of ORMs for document-oriented databases are called object-document mappers (ODMs).
[src:tortoise-orm/object-relational-mapping] Document-oriented databases also prevent the user from having to "shred" objects into table rows.
[src:tortoise-orm/object-relational-mapping] Many of these systems also support the XQuery query language to retrieve datasets.
[src:tortoise-orm/object-relational-mapping] Object-oriented databases tend to be used in complex, niche applications.
[src:tortoise-orm/object-relational-mapping] One of the arguments against using an OODBMS is that it may not be able to execute ad-hoc, application-independent queries.
[src:tortoise-orm/object-relational-mapping] For this reason, many programmers find themselves more at home with an object-SQL mapping system, even though most object-oriented databases are able to process SQL queries to a limited extent.
[src:tortoise-orm/object-relational-mapping] Other OODBMS provide replication to SQL databases, as a means of addressing the need for ad-hoc queries, while preserving well-known query patterns.
[src:tortoise-orm/object-relational-mapping] A variety of difficulties arise when considering how to match an object system to a relational database.
[src:tortoise-orm/object-relational-mapping] These difficulties are referred to as the object–relational impedance mismatch.
[src:tortoise-orm/object-relational-mapping] An alternative to implementing ORM is use of the native procedural languages provided with every major database.
[src:tortoise-orm/object-relational-mapping] These can be called from the client using SQL statements.
[src:tortoise-orm/object-relational-mapping] The Data Access Object (DAO) design pattern is used to abstract these statements and offer a lightweight object-oriented interface to the rest of the application.
[src:tortoise-orm/object-relational-mapping] ORMs are limited to their predefined functionality, which may not cover all edge cases or database features.
[src:tortoise-orm/object-relational-mapping] They usually mitigate this limitation by providing users with an interface to write raw queries, such as Django ORM.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] A **relational database** (**RDB**) is a database based on the relational model of data, as proposed by E.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] A Relational Database Management System (RDBMS) is a type of database management system that stores data in a structured format using rows and columns.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Many relational database systems are equipped with the option of using SQL (Structured Query Language) for querying and updating the database.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] The concept of relational database was defined by E.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Codd introduced the term *relational* in his research paper "A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks".
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] In this paper and later papers, he defined what he meant by *relation*.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] One well-known definition of what constitutes a relational database system is composed of Codd's 12 rules.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Provide relational operators to manipulate the data in tabular form.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] In 1974, IBM began developing System R, a research project to develop a prototype RDBMS.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] The first system sold as an RDBMS was Multics Relational Data Store (June 1976).
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Oracle was released in 1979 by Relational Software, now Oracle Corporation.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Other examples of an RDBMS include IBM Db2, SAP Sybase ASE, and Informix.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] In 1984, the first RDBMS for Macintosh began being developed, code-named Silver Surfer, and was released in 1987 as 4th Dimension and known today as 4D.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] The most common definition of an RDBMS is a product that presents a view of data as a collection of rows and columns, even if it is not based strictly upon relational theory.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] By this definition, RDBMS products typically implement some but not all of Codd's 12 rules.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] A second school of thought argues that if a database does not implement all of Codd's rules (or the current understanding on the relational model, as expressed by Christopher J.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Date, Hugh Darwen and others), it is not relational.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] This view, shared by many theorists and other strict adherents to Codd's principles, would disqualify most DBMSs as not relational.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] For clarification, they often refer to some RDBMSs as *truly-relational database management systems* (TRDBMS), naming others *pseudo-relational database management systems* (PRDBMS).
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] As of 2009, most commercial relational DBMSs employ SQL as their query language.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Alternative query languages have been proposed and implemented, notably the pre-1996 implementation of Ingres QUEL.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] A relational model organizes data into one or more tables (or "relations") of columns and rows, with a unique key identifying each row.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Generally, each table/relation represents one "entity type" (such as customer or product).
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] The rows represent instances of that type of entity (such as "Lee" or "chair") and the columns represent values attributed to that instance (such as address or price).
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Each row in a table has its own unique key.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Rows in a table can be linked to rows in other tables by adding a column for the unique key of the linked row (such columns are known as foreign keys).
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Codd showed that data relationships of arbitrary complexity can be represented by a simple set of concepts.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Part of this processing involves consistently being able to select or modify one and only one row in a table.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Therefore, most physical implementations have a unique primary key (PK) for each row in a table.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] When a new row is written to the table, a new unique value for the primary key is generated; this is the key that the system uses primarily for accessing the table.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] System performance is optimized for PKs.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Other, more natural keys may also be identified and defined as alternate keys (AK).
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Often several columns are needed to form an AK (this is one reason why a single integer column is usually made the PK).
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Both PKs and AKs have the ability to uniquely identify a row within a table.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Additional technology may be applied to ensure a unique ID across the world, a globally unique identifier, when there are broader system requirements.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] The primary keys within a database are used to define the relationships among the tables.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] When a PK migrates to another table, it becomes a foreign key (FK) in the other table.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] When each cell can contain only one value and the PK migrates into a regular entity table, this design pattern can represent either a one-to-one or one-to-many relationship.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Most relational database designs resolve many-to-many relationships by creating an additional table that contains the PKs from both of the other entity tables – the relationship becomes an entity; the resolution table is then named appropriately and the two FKs are combined to form a PK.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] The migration of PKs to other tables is the second major reason why system-assigned integers are used normally as PKs; there is usually neither efficiency nor clarity in migrating a bunch of other types of columns.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Relationships are a logical connection between different tables (entities), established on the basis of interaction among these tables.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] These relationships can be modelled as an entity-relationship model.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] In order for a database management system (DBMS) to operate efficiently and accurately, it must use ACID transactions.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Part of the programming within an RDBMS is accomplished using stored procedures (SPs).
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Often procedures can be used to greatly reduce the amount of information transferred within and outside of a system.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] For increased security, the system design may grant access to only the stored procedures and not directly to the tables.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Fundamental stored procedures contain the logic needed to insert new and update existing data.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] More complex procedures may be written to implement additional rules and logic related to processing or selecting the data.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] The relational database was first defined in June 1970 by Edgar Codd, of IBM's San Jose Research Laboratory.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Codd's view of what qualifies as an RDBMS is summarized in Codd's 12 rules.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] A relational database has become the predominant type of database.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Other models besides the *relational model* include the hierarchical database model and the network model.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] In a relational database, a *relation* is a set of tuples that have the same attributes.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] A tuple usually represents an object and information about that object.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Objects are typically physical objects or concepts.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] A relation is usually described as a table, which is organized into rows and columns.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] All the data referenced by an attribute are in the same domain and conform to the same constraints.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] The relational model specifies that the tuples of a relation have no specific order and that the tuples, in turn, impose no order on the attributes.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Applications access data by specifying queries, which use operations such as *select* to identify tuples, *project* to identify attributes, and *join* to combine relations.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Relations can be modified using the *insert*, *delete*, and *update* operators.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] New tuples can supply explicit values or be derived from a query.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Similarly, queries identify tuples for updating or deleting.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] If the tuple contains a candidate or primary key then obviously it is unique; however, a primary key need not be defined for a row or record to be a tuple.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] The definition of a tuple requires that it be unique, but does not require a primary key to be defined.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Because a tuple is unique, its attributes by definition constitute a superkey.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] All data are stored and accessed via relations.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Relations that store data are called "base relations", and in implementations are called "tables".
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Other relations do not store data, but are computed by applying relational operations to other relations.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] These relations are sometimes called "derived relations".
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] In implementations these are called "views" or "queries".
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Derived relations are convenient in that they act as a single relation, even though they may grab information from several relations.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Also, derived relations can be used as an abstraction layer.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] A domain describes the set of possible values for a given attribute, and can be considered a constraint on the value of the attribute.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Mathematically, attaching a domain to an attribute means that any value for the attribute must be an element of the specified set.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] The character string *"ABC"*, for instance, is not in the integer domain, but the integer value *123* is.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Another example of domain describes the possible values for the field "CoinFace" as ("Heads","Tails").
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] So, the field "CoinFace" will not accept input values like (0,1) or (H,T).
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Constraints are often used to make it possible to further restrict the domain of an attribute.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] For instance, a constraint can restrict a given integer attribute to values between 1 and 10.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Constraints provide one method of implementing business rules in the database and support subsequent data use within the application layer.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] SQL implements constraint functionality in the form of check constraints.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Constraints restrict the data that can be stored in relations.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] These are usually defined using expressions that result in a Boolean value, indicating whether or not the data satisfies the constraint.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Constraints can apply to single attributes, to a tuple (restricting combinations of attributes) or to an entire relation.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Since every attribute has an associated domain, there are constraints (**domain constraints**).
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] The two principal rules for the relational model are known as **entity integrity** and **referential integrity**.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Every relation/table has a primary key, this being a consequence of a relation being a set.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] A primary key uniquely specifies a tuple within a table.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] While natural attributes (attributes used to describe the data being entered) are sometimes good primary keys, surrogate keys are often used instead.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] A surrogate key is an artificial attribute assigned to an object which uniquely identifies it (for instance, in a table of information about students at a school they might all be assigned a student ID in order to differentiate them).
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] The surrogate key has no intrinsic (inherent) meaning, but rather is useful through its ability to uniquely identify a tuple.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Another common occurrence, especially in regard to N:M cardinality is the composite key.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] A composite key is a key made up of two or more attributes within a table that (together) uniquely identify a record.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Foreign key refers to a field in a relational table that matches the primary key column of another table.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Foreign keys need not have unique values in the referencing relation.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] A foreign key can be used to cross-reference tables, and it effectively uses the values of attributes in the referenced relation to restrict the domain of one or more attributes in the referencing relation.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] A stored procedure is executable code that is associated with, and generally stored in, the database.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Stored procedures usually collect and customize common operations, like inserting a tuple into a relation, gathering statistical information about usage patterns, or encapsulating complex business logic and calculations.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Frequently they are used as an application programming interface (API) for security or simplicity.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Implementations of stored procedures on SQL RDBMS's often allow developers to take advantage of procedural extensions (often vendor-specific) to the standard declarative SQL syntax.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Stored procedures are not part of the relational database model, but all commercial implementations include them.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] An index is one way of providing quicker access to data.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Indices can be created on any combination of attributes on a relation.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Queries that filter using those attributes can find matching tuples directly using the index (similar to Hash table lookup), without having to check each tuple in turn.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] This is analogous to using the index of a book to go directly to the page on which the information you are looking for is found, so that you do not have to read the entire book to find what you are looking for.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Relational databases typically supply multiple indexing techniques, each of which is optimal for some combination of data distribution, relation size, and typical access pattern.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Indices are usually implemented via B+ trees, R-trees, and bitmaps.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Indices are usually not considered part of the database, as they are considered an implementation detail, though indices are usually maintained by the same group that maintains the other parts of the database.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] The use of efficient indexes on both primary and foreign keys can dramatically improve query performance.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] This is because B-tree indexes result in query times proportional to log(n) where n is the number of rows in a table and hash indexes result in constant time queries (no size dependency as long as the relevant part of the index fits into memory).
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Queries made against the relational database, and the derived relvars in the database are expressed in a relational calculus or a relational algebra.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] In his original relational algebra, Codd introduced eight relational operators in two groups of four operators each.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Other operators have been introduced or proposed since Codd's introduction of the original eight including relational comparison operators and extensions that offer support for nesting and hierarchical data, among others.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Normalization was first proposed by Codd as an integral part of the relational model.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] It encompasses a set of procedures designed to eliminate non-simple domains (non-atomic values) and the redundancy (duplication) of data, which in turn prevents data manipulation anomalies and loss of data integrity.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] The most common forms of normalization applied to databases are called the normal forms.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Connolly and Begg define database management system (DBMS) as a "software system that enables users to define, create, maintain and control access to the database".
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] RDBMS is an extension of that initialism that is sometimes used when the underlying database is relational.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] An alternative definition for a **relational database management system** is a database management system (DBMS) based on the relational model.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Most databases in widespread use today are based on this model.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] RDBMSs have been a common option for the storage of information in databases used for financial records, manufacturing and logistical information, personnel data, and other applications since the 1980s.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Relational databases have often replaced legacy hierarchical databases and network databases, because RDBMS were easier to implement and administer.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] However, due to the expanse of technologies, such as horizontal scaling of computer clusters, NoSQL databases have recently become popular as an alternative to RDBMS databases.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] Distributed Relational Database Architecture (DRDA) was designed by a workgroup within IBM in the period 1988 to 1994.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] DRDA enables network connected relational databases to cooperate to fulfill SQL requests.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] The messages, protocols, and structural components of DRDA are defined by the Distributed Data Management Architecture.
[src:tortoise-orm/relational-database] According to research company Gartner, in 2011, the five leading proprietary software relational database vendors by revenue were Oracle (48.8%), IBM (20.2%), Microsoft (17.0%), SAP including Sybase (4.6%), and Teradata (3.7%).
